241
00:10:39,660 --> 00:10:42,060
and then also plans
out the optimal way

242
00:10:42,060 --> 00:10:43,150
to structure this query.

243
00:10:43,150 --> 00:10:47,290
How should this query be
optimized and then executed?

244
00:10:47,290 --> 00:10:50,700
And ideally, I should figure out
a way that-- or the leader node,

245
00:10:50,700 --> 00:10:53,460
really, should figure out a
way, such that it can optimally

246
00:10:53,460 --> 00:10:55,770
delegate this task
to many member nodes.

247
00:10:55,770 --> 00:10:57,765
The more it can be
parallelized, the faster

248
00:10:57,765 --> 00:10:59,640
this should be able to
run, because, the idea

249
00:10:59,640 --> 00:11:01,950
is that most of the
things we're doing,

250
00:11:01,950 --> 00:11:03,930
or at least a lot of
the things we could do,

251
00:11:03,930 --> 00:11:05,770
can be parallelized.

252
00:11:05,770 --> 00:11:08,130
And what I mean by
parallelize, if you're not

253
00:11:08,130 --> 00:11:12,030
familiar with that concept,
is that in computing,

254
00:11:12,030 --> 00:11:16,210
if I want to,
gosh, I don't know,

255
00:11:16,210 --> 00:11:20,690
log into my bank, that has
to happen sequentially.

256
00:11:20,690 --> 00:11:22,540
I have to go to the website.

257
00:11:22,540 --> 00:11:25,000
I have to click
the login button.

258
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:28,670
I have to type in my
username and my password.

259
00:11:28,670 --> 00:11:30,470
I have to click Submit.

260
00:11:30,470 --> 00:11:33,160
Then there's likely going to be
a two-factor authentication that

261
00:11:33,160 --> 00:11:35,180
sends a message to my phone.

262
00:11:35,180 --> 00:11:37,660
I agree to it, and then
that sends that back

263
00:11:37,660 --> 00:11:38,720
and it logs me in.

264
00:11:38,720 --> 00:11:41,200
All of those steps have
to happen in order.

265
00:11:41,200 --> 00:11:44,500
There's no way that I can do
each of those steps all at

266
00:11:44,500 --> 00:11:46,810
once because they kind of
rely on the previous step

267
00:11:46,810 --> 00:11:48,730
to be confirmed.

268
00:11:48,730 --> 00:11:50,540
That is a serial process.

269
00:11:50,540 --> 00:11:52,300
That is in order.

270
00:11:52,300 --> 00:11:54,310
Nothing I can do about
that to speed it up,

271
00:11:54,310 --> 00:11:56,620
outside of speed up
the individual steps.

272
00:11:56,620 --> 00:11:59,122
A parallelizable
process, which is not

273
00:11:59,122 --> 00:12:00,580
a word I want to
say 10 times fast,

274
00:12:00,580 --> 00:12:04,150
parallelizable, a
parallelizable process

275
00:12:04,150 --> 00:12:07,930
is something where
doing one thing

276
00:12:07,930 --> 00:12:10,880
isn't dependent upon the
other thing happening.

277
00:12:10,880 --> 00:12:14,870
Let's say that I have, I don't
know, a bunch of timesheets

278
00:12:14,870 --> 00:12:15,980
that I have to approve.

279
00:12:15,980 --> 00:12:18,530
I'm a massive corporation and
I have a bunch of time sheets

280
00:12:18,530 --> 00:12:19,650
I have to approve.

281
00:12:19,650 --> 00:12:21,350
The only thing
I'm looking for is

282
00:12:21,350 --> 00:12:24,920
where there any
flags for managers

283
00:12:24,920 --> 00:12:28,760
and/or did somebody go
over 40 hours a week.

284
00:12:28,760 --> 00:12:32,720
And so the way I do this then is
rather than going from employee

285
00:12:32,720 --> 00:12:35,120
one to employee two to
employee three, well,

286
00:12:35,120 --> 00:12:37,080
I just calculate
all those at once.

287
00:12:37,080 --> 00:12:39,170
I say-- for example,
I could have

288
00:12:39,170 --> 00:12:43,670
one leader computer
that would say, OK, here

289
00:12:43,670 --> 00:12:46,440
are all the 10 million
employees we have.

290
00:12:46,440 --> 00:12:49,130
It's a massive company,
10 million employees.

291
00:12:49,130 --> 00:12:51,390
I have 1,000 computers.

292
00:12:51,390 --> 00:12:54,870
And so what I'll do is I'll
evenly split up each of those 10

293
00:12:54,870 --> 00:12:58,760
million employees to
those 1,000 computers.

294
00:12:58,760 --> 00:13:01,130
And maybe for whatever
reason, my software

295
00:13:01,130 --> 00:13:04,050
can't handle doing more than
one timesheet at a time.

296
00:13:04,050 --> 00:13:06,920
That's OK as long as I can
spread it across those 1,000

297
00:13:06,920 --> 00:13:07,700
computers.

298
00:13:07,700 --> 00:13:09,890
Then it'll go a thousand
times faster than

299
00:13:09,890 --> 00:13:12,260
if I had to do this
all at once or I had

300
00:13:12,260 --> 00:13:14,070
to do this all on one machine.

301
00:13:14,070 --> 00:13:17,350
So that's this idea about
parallelizing a process.

302
00:13:17,350 --> 00:13:20,460
And so Redshift is
specifically designed

303
00:13:20,460 --> 00:13:25,740
to parallelize our queries,
our operations that we're

304
00:13:25,740 --> 00:13:26,920
going to perform.

305
00:13:26,920 --> 00:13:29,100
And the nice thing
is it integrates

306
00:13:29,100 --> 00:13:33,870
a lot of standard
analytical calculations

307
00:13:33,870 --> 00:13:36,607
that you might want to do
into its querying structure.

308
00:13:36,607 --> 00:13:38,940
Meaning that it kind of limits
the amount of extra stuff

309
00:13:38,940 --> 00:13:40,600
I have to do
outside of Redshift.

310
00:13:40,600 --> 00:13:45,210
I can do a lot of stuff just
baked into Redshift right away.

311
00:13:45,210 --> 00:13:46,660
Oops, I lost my screen here.

312
00:13:46,660 --> 00:13:48,740
There we go.

313
00:13:48,740 --> 00:13:54,290
So again, this is
kind of a visual image

314
00:13:54,290 --> 00:13:56,780
of what Redshift
looks like or what it

315
00:13:56,780 --> 00:13:58,260
looks like Redshift is doing.

316
00:13:58,260 --> 00:14:00,567
So, again, client
application setup here,

317
00:14:00,567 --> 00:14:02,900
that might be me sitting at
my computer, typing a query.

318
00:14:02,900 --> 00:14:05,160
That might be some application
running in the cloud.

319
00:14:05,160 --> 00:14:07,410
That might be some application
running on my computer.

320
00:14:07,410 --> 00:14:09,050
It could be anything.

321
00:14:09,050 --> 00:14:12,330
Then we're going to set up some
sort of database connection--

322
00:14:12,330 --> 00:14:17,370
database connection, sorry,
to the machine itself.

323
00:14:17,370 --> 00:14:22,670
And so ODBC stands for
Open Database Connectivity.

324
00:14:22,670 --> 00:14:27,050
And JDBC is Java
Database Connectivity.

325
00:14:27,050 --> 00:14:29,060
And that just is
the kind of language

326
00:14:29,060 --> 00:14:31,422
that's used to communicate
between the application

327
00:14:31,422 --> 00:14:32,130
and the software.

328
00:14:32,130 --> 00:14:34,580
So you can set up an Open
Database Connection or a Java

329
00:14:34,580 --> 00:14:37,160
Database Connection, depending
on what language you're using.

330
00:14:37,160 --> 00:14:40,190
And that is how
you'll make requests

331
00:14:40,190 --> 00:14:45,170
in the language of the data-- of
the data warehouse, the Redshift

332
00:14:45,170 --> 00:14:46,490
instance.

333
00:14:46,490 --> 00:14:49,050
And so, again, those
commands and those queries

334
00:14:49,050 --> 00:14:51,600
are going to be sent
to the leader node.

335
00:14:51,600 --> 00:14:54,300
And then the leader node
says, let me pass those out

336
00:14:54,300 --> 00:14:57,210
to a bunch of
different compute nodes

337
00:14:57,210 --> 00:15:01,320
that exist within my cluster.

338
00:15:01,320 --> 00:15:02,280
Oops.

339
00:15:02,280 --> 00:15:05,790
And so starting at the
leader node side of things,

340
00:15:05,790 --> 00:15:07,510
this is kind of what it's doing.

341
00:15:07,510 --> 00:15:09,870
So, again, like I
said, it's handling

342
00:15:09,870 --> 00:15:12,300
all external and
internal communication.

343
00:15:12,300 --> 00:15:14,430
Internal communication
being the communication

344
00:15:14,430 --> 00:15:15,870
within the cluster.

345
00:15:15,870 --> 00:15:18,060
External communication
being the communication

346
00:15:18,060 --> 00:15:21,500
out to the client or the
tools that we're using.

347
00:15:21,500 --> 00:15:25,070
It comes up with that query
execution plan whenever a query

348
00:15:25,070 --> 00:15:26,330
is submitted to the cluster.

349
00:15:26,330 --> 00:15:29,120
And then once it has
that plan figured out,

350
00:15:29,120 --> 00:15:31,880
it delegates those
tasks, distributes them

351
00:15:31,880 --> 00:15:35,330
amongst the compute nodes,
but also, importantly,

352
00:15:35,330 --> 00:15:37,710
it also distributes
the slices of data.

353
00:15:37,710 --> 00:15:40,820
So each of those compute nodes
will handle some number of--

354
00:15:40,820 --> 00:15:42,300
some number of slices of data.

355
00:15:42,300 --> 00:15:44,960
So this is just kind of an
extra step of parallelization.

356
00:15:44,960 --> 00:15:47,040
So we can parallelize
across the compute nodes,

357
00:15:47,040 --> 00:15:50,280
but also these compute nodes
themselves are computers.

358
00:15:50,280 --> 00:15:52,970
They can also-- themselves, they
might have multiple processors,

359
00:15:52,970 --> 00:15:55,790
multiple cores, so they
can probably also handle

360
00:15:55,790 --> 00:15:57,270
multiple slices at once.

361
00:15:57,270 --> 00:15:59,690
And so the idea is that we
parallelize across the nodes,

362
00:15:59,690 --> 00:16:02,670
and within the nodes, we
parallelize across the slices.

363
00:16:02,670 --> 00:16:05,330
And so the hope is that the
operations we're performing

364
00:16:05,330 --> 00:16:07,880
can be completed on the
slices independently,

365
00:16:07,880 --> 00:16:10,640
and then we just send back
the relevant information

366
00:16:10,640 --> 00:16:13,130
to the leader node.

367
00:16:13,130 --> 00:16:14,870
And so, like I said,
those compute nodes,

368
00:16:14,870 --> 00:16:17,210
they handle the actual
execution of the queries,

369
00:16:17,210 --> 00:16:20,330
though the plan is made
by the leader node.

370
00:16:20,330 --> 00:16:21,852
And then they
execute the queries,

371
00:16:21,852 --> 00:16:23,810
return those intermediate
results to the leader

372
00:16:23,810 --> 00:16:25,430
node for aggregation.

373
00:16:25,430 --> 00:16:28,010
And we have two different
types of compute nodes

374
00:16:28,010 --> 00:16:29,010
we can choose from.

375
00:16:29,010 --> 00:16:32,130
So we can choose from dense
storage and dense compute nodes.

376
00:16:32,130 --> 00:16:34,173
And so dense storage
nodes are exactly

377
00:16:34,173 --> 00:16:35,840
like they say-- they're
basically trying

378
00:16:35,840 --> 00:16:38,070
to optimize storage for price.

379
00:16:38,070 --> 00:16:39,900
So it's dense in
the terms of price.

380
00:16:39,900 --> 00:16:42,290
A hard drive-- a hard
disk drive is much larger

381
00:16:42,290 --> 00:16:44,240
than a solid state
drive, but it's

382
00:16:44,240 --> 00:16:46,700
trying to create
the largest data

383
00:16:46,700 --> 00:16:49,650
warehouse possible for
the lowest price possible.

384
00:16:49,650 --> 00:16:52,290
So that's called the dense
storage compute node.

385
00:16:52,290 --> 00:16:57,170
And the dense compute
ones sacrifice price

386
00:16:57,170 --> 00:16:58,770
in the name of efficiency.

387
00:16:58,770 --> 00:17:01,250
So if you know this is a really
high-performance workload,

388
00:17:01,250 --> 00:17:03,127
you need to have
that high throughput,

389
00:17:03,127 --> 00:17:05,210
you're going to have to
go with the dense compute.

390
00:17:05,210 --> 00:17:08,650
That's going to give you
your fastest performance.

391
00:17:08,650 --> 00:17:10,359
And then, like I said,
each compute node

392
00:17:10,359 --> 00:17:13,000
is going to have multiple
slices with each slice utilizing

393
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:16,047
a portion of the node's
memory and disk space.

394
00:17:16,047 --> 00:17:18,130
So it's almost partitioning
out itself and saying,

395
00:17:18,130 --> 00:17:19,182
OK, well, I can handle--

396
00:17:19,182 --> 00:17:21,640
I have enough memory to handle
a couple of different slices

397
00:17:21,640 --> 00:17:22,640
of this size.

398
00:17:22,640 --> 00:17:25,329
And I can operate on each
of those in parallel,

399
00:17:25,329 --> 00:17:27,520
independent of each other.

400
00:17:27,520 --> 00:17:29,290
And then the type
of node, obviously,

401
00:17:29,290 --> 00:17:31,090
is going to determine
how many slices

402
00:17:31,090 --> 00:17:34,520
and what size those slices
are per the compute node.

403
00:17:34,520 --> 00:17:37,780
So the more you can have on
a-- or the larger the instance,

404
00:17:37,780 --> 00:17:39,980
the more slices you can
have per compute node.

405
00:17:39,980 --> 00:17:42,160
But this is kind of the
trade-off-- there actually

406
00:17:42,160 --> 00:17:43,870
is kind of an
interesting optimization

407
00:17:43,870 --> 00:17:46,270
problem within this,
of saying, well,

408
00:17:46,270 --> 00:17:50,800
let's take the extreme example
of one really, really powerful

409
00:17:50,800 --> 00:17:53,080
computer as our compute node.

410
00:17:53,080 --> 00:17:55,180
And that one really,
really powerful computer

411
00:17:55,180 --> 00:17:59,240
has a lot of ability to handle
a bunch of different slices.

412
00:17:59,240 --> 00:18:01,510
So conceivably, we wouldn't
even need to pass it out

413
00:18:01,510 --> 00:18:03,610
to a bunch of compute
nodes, but the idea

414
00:18:03,610 --> 00:18:08,450
is that the effort to create
such a reliable and capable

415
00:18:08,450 --> 00:18:12,020
system is much more expensive
than maybe me creating

416
00:18:12,020 --> 00:18:17,480
a bunch of smaller instances,
a bunch of small compute nodes

417
00:18:17,480 --> 00:18:19,700
that are very, very
cheap and I can almost

418
00:18:19,700 --> 00:18:20,910
have them be redundant.

419
00:18:20,910 --> 00:18:23,243
And to some extent, you will
have a level of redundancy,

420
00:18:23,243 --> 00:18:26,930
such that I could send the same
slice of data to another machine

421
00:18:26,930 --> 00:18:29,090
or to five different
machines and just say, "Well,

422
00:18:29,090 --> 00:18:31,673
I hope you guys all come up with
the same result or you should

423
00:18:31,673 --> 00:18:34,410
come up with the same result,"
and then I'll just verify that.

424
00:18:34,410 --> 00:18:35,990
And that gives me,
actually, some really nice

425
00:18:35,990 --> 00:18:37,730
statistical properties
to ensure that I

426
00:18:37,730 --> 00:18:40,370
get the best result possible
or the most appropriate result

427
00:18:40,370 --> 00:18:43,140
possible while also
minimizing the cost.

428
00:18:43,140 --> 00:18:46,490
So that's one of the reasons
why this distributed computing

429
00:18:46,490 --> 00:18:52,030
structure architecture is so
critical in analytics workloads.

430
00:18:52,030 --> 00:18:54,160
And so, yeah, our
multiple compute nodes

431
00:18:54,160 --> 00:18:57,790
now can execute that same query
code and portion of the data,

432
00:18:57,790 --> 00:19:01,840
maximize parallel processing,
and minimize those costs,

433
00:19:01,840 --> 00:19:03,075
and really compute time.

434
00:19:06,520 --> 00:19:09,490
Another unique
component of Redshift

435
00:19:09,490 --> 00:19:12,920
is that it utilizes
columnar-based data storage.

436
00:19:12,920 --> 00:19:16,540
So most SQL databases
you're familiar with--

437
00:19:16,540 --> 00:19:19,420
MySQL, Microsoft SQL Server--

438
00:19:19,420 --> 00:19:22,120
all of those are
row-based storage systems,

439
00:19:22,120 --> 00:19:23,780
whether you realized it or not.

440
00:19:23,780 --> 00:19:25,655
Think about what they're
really trying to do.

441
00:19:25,655 --> 00:19:27,830
They're trying to handle
transaction-level data

442
00:19:27,830 --> 00:19:29,915
one row at a time, one
transaction at a time.

443
00:19:29,915 --> 00:19:31,790
And that transaction
might be an actual sale.

444
00:19:31,790 --> 00:19:33,415
It might be a user
hitting our website.

445
00:19:33,415 --> 00:19:34,870
It could be any
number of things,

446
00:19:34,870 --> 00:19:37,330
but it's at the row level.

447
00:19:37,330 --> 00:19:39,850
And this is actually really,
really efficient for querying

448
00:19:39,850 --> 00:19:42,010
for most standard queries
that you are probably

449
00:19:42,010 --> 00:19:42,920
used to running.

450
00:19:42,920 --> 00:19:45,560
That's the best way
to store that data.

451
00:19:45,560 --> 00:19:49,580
It allows it to identify
primary keys and sort

452
00:19:49,580 --> 00:19:51,020
and search very, very quickly.

453
00:19:51,020 --> 00:19:53,770
And so that is one of the
reasons why they do leverage

454
00:19:53,770 --> 00:19:55,300
that row-based storage.

455
00:19:55,300 --> 00:19:57,230
But Redshift does
something a bit different.

456
00:19:57,230 --> 00:20:00,310
It stores it in a columnar-based
fashion, which the idea here

457
00:20:00,310 --> 00:20:03,370
is that the columns kind
of matter a little bit more

458
00:20:03,370 --> 00:20:06,500
in the context of an analytics
workload because our columns

459
00:20:06,500 --> 00:20:07,835
are our variables now.

460
00:20:07,835 --> 00:20:09,210
They're the things
that can vary.

461
00:20:09,210 --> 00:20:11,002
We're looking at this
as a big picture now.

462
00:20:11,002 --> 00:20:13,520
We're not looking at an
individual transaction level.

463
00:20:13,520 --> 00:20:16,460
And by storing in a
columnar-based fashion,

464
00:20:16,460 --> 00:20:22,460
it will dramatically reduce the
input/output time on our disks

465
00:20:22,460 --> 00:20:24,560
when we're running
any sort of query,

466
00:20:24,560 --> 00:20:26,450
as well as the amount
of data we need to load

467
00:20:26,450 --> 00:20:28,765
into memory to execute a query.

468
00:20:28,765 --> 00:20:32,540
I don't need to know everything
to even-- for example,

469
00:20:32,540 --> 00:20:35,390
if I wanted to
start sorting data,

470
00:20:35,390 --> 00:20:39,080
I don't need to wait till I
have loaded in all the rows,

471
00:20:39,080 --> 00:20:41,850
including all the values
for each of those rows.

472
00:20:41,850 --> 00:20:44,830
I can just load in
one column at a time,

473
00:20:44,830 --> 00:20:46,550
or I can just load in
the one column that

474
00:20:46,550 --> 00:20:50,030
matters, sort that one, and
then map it back if necessary

475
00:20:50,030 --> 00:20:51,510
to return other columns.

476
00:20:51,510 --> 00:20:53,060
But the idea is
that I can just do

477
00:20:53,060 --> 00:20:56,410
what I need because I might
just need to print out

478
00:20:56,410 --> 00:20:58,160
a bunch of sorted
values, and therefore, I

479
00:20:58,160 --> 00:21:00,440
don't need to return
every single row with all

480
00:21:00,440 --> 00:21:02,180
the values in each row.

481
00:21:02,180 --> 00:21:04,160
And so the
columnar-based fashion--

482
00:21:04,160 --> 00:21:08,000
the columnar-based storage is
much more efficient for that.

483
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:11,290
If you're familiar with R, or
in Python, you might have seen--

484
00:21:11,290 --> 00:21:13,487
I think we have used Pandas now.

485
00:21:13,487 --> 00:21:15,820
I can't remember if we've
used Pandas explicitly or not,

486
00:21:15,820 --> 00:21:17,862
or maybe even talked about
it, but Pandas is just

487
00:21:17,862 --> 00:21:20,720
another columnar-based
storage system.

488
00:21:20,720 --> 00:21:22,630
It's dataframes.

489
00:21:22,630 --> 00:21:25,580
Those are-- better statement--

